Project: Personal Loan Campaign Modelling¶

Objective:

  • create a model to determine which customers have a higher probability of purchasing the loan
  • predict whether a liability customer will buy a personal loan or not
  • detemine which variables are most significant
  • determine which segment of customers should be targeted more

Testing the assumptions of logistic regression¶

  • In this section, I will test the assumptions of logistic regression:
    1. is the dependent variable binary?
    2. is there a large sample size?
    3. is there an absence of mulitcollinearity?

Answering logistic regressison assumption¶

  1. The dependent variable is binary: either the curtomer took the loan or did not
  2. The sample size is large (5000 independent observations)
  3. Abscence of multicollinearity (below)

Insights on model performance evaluation and improvement¶

  • According to the VIF, age or experience were highly multicollinear
  • when the logistic regression analysis is done with the removal of the "age" column, the odds ratio is a little more representative on the final analysis:
    • The odds ratio of income is 0.035
    • The odds ratio of family is 0.034
    • the odds ratio of education is 0.038
    • an image of the odds ratio with the "age" column remove can be found here:
  • however, if these columns were excluded from the analysis, the logistic regression model was not a good fit on the data
  • therefore, these columns were kept in
  • based on the results of the logistic regression and the decision tree, the columns for age and experience were not important, so keeping this data will not profoundly impact the final analysis

Takeaways from logistic regression and the confusion matrix¶

  • Our logistic regression fit the test data well at 0.918

  • However, since the coefficients dont mean much, we can not tell true relationships between the data

  • True Positives (TP): we correctly predicted that the customers took a loan: 42

  • True Negatives (TN): we correctly predicted that the customers didn't take a loan: 1335

  • False Positives (FP)/Type I error: we incorrectly predicted that the customers took a loan: 27

  • False Negatives (FN)/Type II error: we incorrectly predicted that they didn't take a loan: 96

In [29]:
scores=[] 
# To get diferent metric scores
from sklearn import metrics
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, recall_score, precision_score, roc_auc_score, roc_curve, confusion_matrix, precision_recall_curve
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

def scores(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
    pred_test = model.predict(X_test)

    train_acc = accuracy_score(pred_train,y_train)
    test_acc = accuracy_score(pred_test,y_test)

    train_recall = recall_score(y_train,pred_train)
    test_recall = recall_score(y_test,pred_test)

    train_precision = precision_score(y_train,pred_train)
    test_precision = precision_score(y_test,pred_test)

    print("Accuracy on training set : ",accuracy_score(pred_train,y_train))
    print("Accuracy on test set : ",accuracy_score(pred_test,y_test), "\n")
    print("Recall on training set : ",recall_score(y_train,pred_train))
    print("Recall on test set : ",recall_score(y_test,pred_test), "\n")
    print("Precision on training set : ",precision_score(y_train,pred_train))
    print("Precision on test set : ",precision_score(y_test,pred_test))

Takeaways from the model performance metrics¶

  • since this is a model on what type of customers to give out loans, we should focus on the instances in which the bank did not give out loans to the customers that should have gotten loans (the false negatives)
  • the most loss for this bank, in this model, will be when they do not give out loans to customers who would have accepted them
  • therefore, this model should focus on imroving recall
  • in the model, as it is, the recall is slightly higher in the training data: 30.7% vs 30.4%
  • To increase the recall , I will look at the odds coefficient and the Precision-Recall curve

optimal_threshold = thresholds[optimal_idx]

def plot_prec_recall_vs_thresh(precisions, recalls, thresholds):
    plt.plot(thresholds, precisions[:-1], 'r', label='precision')
    plt.plot(thresholds, recalls[:-1], 'b', label = 'recall')
    plt.xlabel('Threshold')
    plt.ylabel("Recall")
    plt.legend(loc='upper right')

Hyperparameter pruning using Grid Search¶

In [54]:
# Choose the type of classifier. 
estimate = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=4)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
## add from article
parameters = {'max_depth': np.arange(1,10), 
              'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 5, 7, 10,15,20],
              'max_leaf_nodes' : [2, 3, 5, 10]
             }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
acc_scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(estimate, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer,cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
estimate = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data. 
estimate.fit(X_train, y_train)

Insights on misclassified data¶

  • it seems that a lot of the misclassified rows had an online banking facility
  • according to the descriptive statistics, all of the misclassified rows for the different models had a higher online banking option than the original data
  • the misclassified rows also had slightly higher family sizes than the original data

Insights on Logistic regression versus Decision trees¶

  • the metric used to compare the two models and trainig vs testing data was recall
  • recall was chosen because the bank takes the largest loss by not offering the loan to customers who would have taken the loan if it were offered
    • in order to decrease this number (the number of false negatives), we must increase the recall score
  • the best test recall score on the logistic regresission analysis was obtained with an optimized regression, and the maximum test recall score was 0.53
  • conversely, the lowest test recall from the decision tree was with a pre pruned tree on a maximum depth (recall = 0.87)
  • the best test recall score was achieved with a post-pruned tree, with a recall score of 0.96

Conclusion and Recomendations for the bank and its marketing team¶

  • Based on the data from the model, the marketing team should focus on the following features when offering loans to increase their revenue from loans:
    • education level
    • income level
    • family size
  • as the values of these features increase, so too will the probability that the customers accept an offered loan
  • the bank will make the most money as they offer customers with a large income, high education level, and increased family size, since they are most likely to accept loans
